1 3. Nonprofit organizations;
2 4. For-profit companies;
3 5. Nongovernment entities partnering with a governmental
4 agency; and
5 6. Tribal governments.
6 B. Those offering harm-reduction services shall register with
7 the State Department of Health and may engage in the following
8 activities in order to reduce the use of drugs, prevent outbreaks of
9 infectious diseases and reduce morbidity among people who use
10 injection drugs:
11 1. Offer referrals and resources to treat substance use
12 disorders;
13 2. Provide education on the risk of transmission of infectious
14 diseases, including human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and viral
15 hepatitis;
16 3. Rapid testing for HIV, hepatitis C and sexually transmitted
17 infections (STIs);
18 4. Referrals for medical and mental health services;
19 5. Collect used hypodermic needles for safe disposal;
20 6. Possess and distribute hypodermic needles, cleaning kits,
21 test kits and opioid antagonists; and
22 7. Rapid substance testing products used, intended for use, or
23 fashioned specifically for the use in identifying or analyzing the
24 potency or toxicity of unknown substances.
